>
>The purpose of this award, which provides up to $300,000 over a five-year
>period, is to support early career researchers for diverse disciplines and
>is intended to facilitate the professional development of early career
>scholars who have some demonstrated success in conducting high quality
>research and who seek to further develop their skills and research program.
>
>Studies from these researchers deepen and broaden the knowledge base in
>areas that contribute to creating a society that values young people and
>helps them live up to their potential. The Foundation funds research on
>topics that are directly related to youth 8-25 years of age.  <>Priority
>areas focus on the effects of contexts on youth development; improving the
>systems, organizations, and programs affecting young people; and adults’
>use of scientific evidence and their views of youth. They are particularly
>interested in research that is interdisciplinary, examines young people in
>social, institutional, community and cultural contexts and that addresses
>questions that advance both theory and practice.  <>
>
>Applicants should be pre-tenure or in a similar early career status if in a
>non-tenure track position.  Applicants must be within 7 years of receipt of
>their terminal degree at the time of application.  At least half of the
>Scholar’s paid time must be spent conducting research.  <>We are permitted
>to nominate one candidate per major division (school) of the University.
>
>If you are interested in being that individual, please forward the follow
>items to Beth H. Israel, Executive Director, OPG
><mailto:bhi1@columbia.edu><bhi1@columbia.edu> no later than 5 PM Friday,
>June 24, 2005:
>
>**Abstract (no more than 5 pages) of the proposed research project(s) and
>career plans, including the roles of this award, if received.
>
>**One-page CV
>     # full name, present position, date of appointment.  Indicate whether
>or not you are tenure track.
>     # Include all degrees (provide institution and eate for each) and honors
>     # Selected publications (list no more than 6)
>     # Mentors (names, addresses and email addressess
>     # References (names and email addresses)
>
>**Full CV
>
>**Plan for mentorship ­ Identify and justify at least one (but up to 3)
>individual who is available to assist you.
>
>**2 published chapters, research reports or journal articles that exemplify
>your research.
>
>**Nomination statement from your department chair indicating the role you
>play in the department and the role you will play in the future; supporting
>people and resources available to you, and the Chair’s assessment of the
>attainability of your research plan.  The statement should include your
>appointment, promotion and institutional support plans, including a
>guarantee that at least 50% of your paid time will be devoted to research.
>
>**Letter from proposed mentor confirming the acceptance of their role
>detailing the nature of the relationship and should not serve as a
>recommendation. The original of this letter will, if you are selected as
>our nominee, have to be sent DIRECTLY to the Foundation; email versions
>should be sent to Beth Israel if at all possible given time constraints.
>
>**IF POSSIBLE (given time constraints), include 3 letters of recommendation
>from individuals other than those proposed as mentors.  The original of
>these letters will, if you are selected as our nominee, have to be sent
>DIRECTLY to the Foundation; email versions should be sent to Beth Israel if
>at all possible.
